    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Okay, lets face it dwarves decks are difficult to master and so is the path to burdens.  I will start my explanation with the shadow side since it is the essence of the deck.<br>
<br>
Shadow<br>
Your main force is composed of Isengard orcs, which you use to inflict some wounds on your enemies. The axes and The trees are strong will contribute to inflict some more damage.  Your goal is not to kill but to get lots of wounds on lots of character.  With Can you protect me from yourself you win either way the opponent chooses so its a very excellent card in the deck.  The 4 twilight nazguls all can wound the ring-bearer if you win skirmishes which will probably already be wounded from your orcs and this has some chances of transfering into burdens.  The Witch-King will almost always win his Skirmishes while enquea is more oeasterlingamble.  Anyway, they lead the way to It wants to be found.  The regular enquea is there to take advantage of the burdens you create and will add wounds on the character.  One of the weakness of the deck is the high twilight cost of the nazgul cards so there is 3 tower of Orthanc for Twilight generating.  So its important to spread the wounds rather than killing companions so you can spot exhausted companions.  This deck may not seem much at the start cause the free people will heal at site 3 and 6 so you will seem very frustrating but after site 6, I can assure you that the burdens will add up pretty quickly and the site 9 which make you draw a card for every burden you spot will insure you can add the last burdens you need.<br>
<br>
Free peoples<br>
The fellowship is composed of dwarves with 0 Twilight tales to boost Gloin and to help vs Moria decks.  The rest is mainly 0 Twilight equipments so you can play practically all your fellowship cards in the same turn, boosting your dwarves without adding too much twilight and cycling your deck to get more shadow.  <br>
<br>
Now for some Dwarf strategies.  First of all, go second.  This deck isn&#39;t made to win by getting to site 9 first.  Stop at each site and take the time to boost your dwarves with the tales and the equipments.  Discard the strength boosting cards against moria decks.  The extra copies of Fror and Farin are there to ensure you have a sufficient fellowship vs moria and other swarms. One of the worst match up for a dwarves deck is nazguls of course so i included a make light of burden and i Should add a Bilbo, well spoken gentle hobbit (just don&#39;t have it).  All you have to do is survive while your shadow relentlessly attack your opponent<br>
<br>
Adventure Path<br>
<br>
Prancing pony : Hey...No Aragorn in my deck you say!  Well, I want to make sure the opponent will add a burden to get his aragorn (every burdens counts)<br>
<br>
Trollshaw Forest : Don&#39;t keep for here the equipments cards you got on the first round, play them on the first round and just play the equipments you get on the second round here.  Your dwarves are just too vulnerable without weapons.<br>
<br>
Frodo&#39;s Bedroom : I&#39;m waiting for a nice dwarf site 3 but it isn&#39;t coming.  At least this one doesn&#39;t help anybody.<br>
<br>
Eregion Hills : Every burdens help so make sure you get this site on the table.<br>
<br>
Bridge : nuff said.<br>
<br>
Galadriel&#39;s glade : not a forest or river, hehe.<br>
<br>
Alduin Wilderland : No archery&#39;s always good<br>
<br>
Gates of Argonath : No ARVs but take care, you can&#39;t play your maneuver events either.<br>
<br>
Summit : You will most probably draw the rest of your deck here to insure you can burden some more.<br>
<br>
I&#39;ll finish by saying this is not an easy deck but it will make you see the potential of dwarves and burdens so if you have any suggestions, don&#39;t hesitate.  I will probably post upgraded version of this deck later.<br>
<br>
